# Slipway Workflow

```
IRON LAW: THIS SKILL ROUTES INTO THE CLI; IT DOES NOT REPLACE THE CLI
```

## Purpose
Use `{{.PublicName}}` as the single exported entry skill for Slipway. It tells
an AI how to enter governed work, how to continue an active change, and when to
hand off to a more specific command surface or governed host skill.

Slipway is a governance CLI for AI-assisted software delivery. A governed
change is the unit of work. `done-ready` means the change has satisfied the
workflow gates and can be finalized; `done` happens only after explicit `slipway done`.

## Layered Surfaces (use the most specific one that fits)
Slipway exposes three AI-facing layers; this skill is only the top entry:
- **This entry skill (`{{.PublicName}}`)** — first contact and routing: decide
  create-vs-continue and pick the right command, then leave as soon as a command
  or governed host owns the step.
- **Command surfaces (`slipway:<command>`)** — one per CLI command with the exact
  arguments and contract; prefer these over re-deriving a command here.
- **Governed host skills (`slipway-<name>`)** — the stage skills the CLI selects
  via `slipway next`/`run` (intake, research, plan-audit, wave-orchestration,
  review, …); never guess these, load the one the CLI returns.

## Primary Route Table
| Situation | Command |
|---|---|
| Unsure whether a governed change already exists | `slipway status --json` |
| No active change and governed work should begin | `slipway new --json` |
| Active change and you need the next governed host without advancing | `slipway next --json` |
| Active change and you want the CLI to advance to the next governed step | `slipway run --json` |
| The change is already `done-ready` and should be finalized | `slipway done` |

## Entry Rules
When starting governed work and you can classify intent directly, enter through
`slipway new --json`.

These are JSON stdin fields for `slipway new --json`, not command-line flags.
Provide them when known:
- `guardrail_domain`
- `complexity`: `trivial`, `simple`, `complex`, or `critical`
- `needs_discovery`

Minimal explicit-classification example:
```bash
echo '{"description":"fix typo","guardrail_domain":"","needs_discovery":false,"complexity":"simple"}' | slipway new --json
```

If these fields are omitted, the CLI applies conservative fallback defaults.

## Runtime Authority Boundaries
- `ResolveNextSkill` selects governed host skills. This skill does not guess or override that selection.
- `commandRegistry` owns command descriptions, arguments, prerequisites, and surface metadata.
- `references/skill-index.md` is informational only. It helps inspect exported host skills; the kernel does not read it back.
- Existing CLI commands remain the only execution surface. This skill never reimplements transitions, gates, or command semantics.

## Handoff After `slipway next --json`
- read the generated SKILL.md for `next_skill.name`
- derive the SKILL.md path from your own tool convention using `slipway-{name}`
- treat the default JSON as an action contract; do not expect diagnostic context fields
- `context_budget` appears only when the guard action is `warn` or `stop`
- if governance controls, policy prose, or full readiness details are needed, run `slipway health --governance --json --change <slug>` or rerun `next/run` with `--diagnostics`
- read policy packs by path; do not expect inline policy-pack prose in default JSON
- do not look for retired agent fields or a second exported prompt file
- do not guess the next governed host without the CLI response

## Delegation Surface
Detailed command contracts live in `references/command-reference.md`. For
commands that ship generated command surfaces, prefer those surfaces over
re-explaining the command inline here.

{{if eq .ToolID "codex"}}For Codex, command surfaces remain global prompt files under
`~/.codex/prompts/slipway-<command>.md`.{{else}}For `{{.ToolID}}`, command surfaces live under the generated workspace command
directory `{{.CommandsDir}}`.{{end}}

CLI-only diagnostics such as `learn`, `stats`, `health`, and `codebase-map` do not have
separate command prompt surfaces; use the generated workflow reference file for
their detailed arguments and prerequisites.

## Skill Index and Host Handoff
- when exported skill navigation is needed, read `{{.SkillIndexPath}}`
- use the index as reference only; it is not progression authority
- public focus aliases listed in the index are command selectors, not host-skill paths
- load a focus-backed support skill only through the command/focus surface unless an exported host `SKILL.md` path exists
- when governed execution is needed, read the host returned by `slipway next --json`
- derive the host skill path from `next_skill.name` using `.codex/skills/slipway-<name>/SKILL.md` or the equivalent local tool convention
- use technique skills as overlays for posture and procedure, not as progression authorities
- once a more specific host, command surface, or technique skill clearly owns the task, leave this entry skill and follow that more specific surface

## Hard Rules
- do not bypass lifecycle gates
- do not treat this workflow skill as progression authority
- do not invent command semantics not present in the CLI
- do not guess the next governed host without `slipway next --json`
- do not duplicate long per-command prose here when the reference file or command surface already owns it
